Answering the questions in exercise 6.1:
1.If Users choose cancel, the pop-up window has shown the message:
"You've chosen: No".
2.If we want to customize the options for the users, we can use the JOptionPane.showOptionDialog
with the documentation is JOptionPane.showOptionDialog(parentComponent, message, title, optionType, messageType, icon, options, initialValue).
Here, we can create an array of options customized by the user corresponding to the parameter "options" in the documentation of showOptionDialog.
For example, we can initialize:
import javax.swing.JOptionPane;

public class test_for_answering {
  public static void main(String args[] ){
    Object[] options = { "I do", "I don't" };
    JOptionPane.showOptionDialog(null, "Are you sure?", "Warning",
    JOptionPane.DEFAULT_OPTION, JOptionPane.WARNING_MESSAGE,
    null, options,options[0]);
    System.exit(0);
    //JOptionPane.showOptionDialog(parentComponent, message, title, optionType, messageType, icon, options, initialValue)
} 

  }
The above code will initialize a window with 2 options "I do", and "I don't". As we can see, the number and content of options can be customized by changing the "options" array.
This array can also take the value input by the user.